body:
The symptom of this crash is that the node is started in full sync mode, but for whatever reason it reverts to fast sync. The fast sync bloom is an acceleration structure that's needed for fast sync, but is not allocated in full mode. The reason we crash is because we try to access this acceleration structure in a mode where it does not exist.

The reason Geth reverts to fast sync is because when it starts up, it sees that there's blocks + receipts in the database, but no state whatsoever beside the genesis. So it assumes, that previously it was started in fast sync and failed. The only way this can happen is if you do a full sync on a very small chain, never flush and then a) crash or b) kill geth without letting it write it's state to disk.

@rfikki Did you by any chance crash your Geth instance the very first time? Or murdered it without letting it write it's state to disk?

@holiman @fjl We can make the fast sync enabling logic a bit smarter by taking into consideration the `syncmode` flag too. When we added the detection logic fast sync was not the default yet, so we needed a way to gracefully resume fast sync even if users stop supplying the flag. That's not the case any more, so we can be smarter with full mode.
